blished in the United States and Canada between 1831 and 1851. She also examines how Walker's Appeal exerted a powerful and lasting influence on William Lloyd Garrison's Liberator and other publications by White antislavery activists.Dinius contends that scholars have neglected the positive, transnational, and transformative effects of Walker's Appeal on print-based political activism and literary and book history—that is, its primarily textual effects—due to an enduringly narrow focus on the violence that the pamphlet may have occasioned. She offers as an alternative a broadened view of activism and resistance that centers the works of Walker, Stewart, Apess, Quinn, Garnet, and Brown within an exploration of radical forms of authorship, publication, civic participation, and resistance. In doing so, she has written a major contribution to African American literary studies and the history of the book in antebellum America.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aAmerican literaturexAfrican American authorsxHistory and criticism. 0aAmerican literaturexIndian authorsxHistory and criticism. 0aAmerican literaturey19th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aAmerican literature-19th century-History and criticism. 0aAmerican literature-African American authors-History and criticism. 0aAmerican literature-Indian authors-History and criticism. 0aAntislavery movements in literature. 0aAntislavery movementszNorth AmericaxHistoryy19th century. 0aAntislavery movements-North America-History-19th century. 0aApess, William,-1798-1839. 0aBrown, Paola,-active 1828-1852. 0aCanadian literaturexBlack authorsxHistory and criticism. 0aCanadian literaturey19th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aCanadian literature-19th century-History and criticism. 0aCanadian literature-Black authors-History and criticism. 0aGarnet, 